The time complexity of this process is described as amortized $O(1)$. In simple words:The "Cheap" Case ($O(1)$): Most append operations are extremely fast because there is already empty space in the current array.The "Expensive" Case ($O(n)$): Occasionally, the array becomes full, triggering a resize. This requires visiting every single item to move it, taking time proportional to the number of elements ($n$).The Amortized Result: Because the capacity doubles each time, these expensive resizes happen less and less frequently as the list grows. When the cost of one $O(n)$ resize is spread out over the many $O(1)$ appends that preceded it, the "average" cost per operation is constant.Linked Lists: Singly and DoublyThe toolkit also implements Linked Lists, which offer a different approach to dynamic data by storing elements in a sequence connected by pointers.Singly Linked List (SLL): This structure supports adding items at the beginning or end and deleting by value. It is particularly efficient for insertions at the head because no shifting of other elements is required.Doubly Linked List (DLL): By adding a "previous" pointer to each node, the DLL allows for more complex operations, such as inserting after a specific node or deleting at a specific index more easily.Abstract Data Types: Stacks and QueuesUsing the Singly Linked List as a foundation, the toolkit implements two major Abstract Data Types (ADTs): the Stack and the Queue.The Stack (LIFO)A Stack follows the Last-In, First-Out principle, similar to a pile of plates.Push/Pop/Peek: All these operations are $O(1)$. By performing these actions at the "head" of the linked list, the toolkit ensures that adding, removing, or viewing the top element takes the same amount of time regardless of how many items are in the stack.The Queue (FIFO)A Queue follows the First-In, First-Out principle, mimicking a real-life waiting line.Enqueue/Dequeue/Front: These are also $O(1)$. To maintain this efficiency, the implementation uses both a head and a tail pointer. This allows the toolkit to add items to the back and remove them from the front instantly, without traversing the entire list.